The pituitary gland is attached to the hypothalamus which monitors large amounts of sensory information from the body systems via the central nervous system (e.g. temperature, hunger and thirst). The overall anatomical structure known as the hypothalamic-pituitary axis a regulatory system and is responsible for homeostasis of the majority of endocrine functions. 
This regulation begins at the hypothalamus, which feeds information from the CNS to the pituitary gland, via parvicellular neurones that secrete releasing hormones into the blood supply of the anterior pituitary gland (superior hypophyseal artery). These releasing hormones simulate or inhibit hormonal secretion (release) from the anterior pituitary into systemic blood system. The pituitary hormones can then go on to further stimulate or inhibit hormone production in the peripheral glands. Later changes in circulating levels of hormones, produced by the effected endocrine glands, can be detected by the hypothalamus, which can then respond by decreasing/increasing its stimulation of the pituitary gland to maintain homeostasis. Feedback control of this axis is known as the parvicellular system and is what regulates the majority of hormonal concentrations within the body.
